[{"id":30616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gThXEaNogFuIoOaRO5q27DvaPrGlwo6LW9NF7U3E0Vc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EojC9Lr8jkzWyq-smlE7kB7WE9fNaNpRLt-qmxOTYTc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/x7ZY35KI48s6cnXp2_re4rxYkUAT2xwdYruzAzCKxIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_6BCuKM51sL2ohKpDp7j3U9wQeFXk6x_XBGA-iyJEWo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The major component of Borsch reagent is 2,4- dinitrophenyl hydrazine which can be obtained by reaction of 2,4-dinitrochloro benzene and hydrazine\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RRG8qBuKpt1U3eB-Jwk7N1jUCKZByAfjwEe-TXAtbBI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/n-lxFT54f0PvQPDekDXp5G7QkLPI-8jeto7HfnBIb_c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30470,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a28b0498-b247-4c00-9edb-a1244c57ce59.png\" style=\"width: 290px; height: 155px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5f6ed249-ffe6-4519-b2a0-2776777b595d.png\" style=\"width: 290px; height: 154px;\"/>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The Hydroboration Oxidation reaction is an organic chemical reaction which is employed for the conversion of alkenes into alcohols that are neutral.</p><p>The hydroboration oxidation reaction mechanism can be considered as an anti-markownikov's reaction where a hydroxyl group attaches itself to the carbon which is less substituted. </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1243050-516e-499d-aea4-1d112e3ec222.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 194px;\"/></p><p>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30463,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CH</mi></math> reacts with sodium an intermediate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><mi>CNa</mi></math> is formed which on further reaction with propyl bromide gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msub><mi>CCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> as the product. The second step of the reaction follows, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> mechanism.</p><p>The reaction is as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eeb0ea7a-8cf1-486d-9f33-ce15143a5e9c.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 205px;\"/></p><p>Hence in the above reaction,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math></p><p>Hence option A is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["mixture of $o-$ and p-bromotoluenes","mixture of $o-$ and p-dibromobenzenes","mixture of $\\mathrm{o}$ - and p-bromoanilines","mixture of 0 - and $\\mathrm{m}$-bromotoluenes"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tVH0Z-BiCO1w4jt8zRXFMiKsPsOaZSEfYTVU4v1nxhA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30577,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/55de67e1-02d0-49d0-aa64-0030c5fb71c2-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9180d02a-aa0b-493f-8b43-f3ea35981546-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 76px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1ab2e50-3762-488f-93e3-accb3f4e82d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93928ad0-be72-4ceb-9af4-742310e61d9e-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 72px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>This reaction is the halohydration of alkene. It is an electrophilic addition reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/61fb1145-f910-4446-bb82-e55aa173bf07-ef335eea-7a20-41d2-ac30-736362ebb571-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 62px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9383e0f-b370-4281-b699-b62221f1f947-image48.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 227px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30484,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mtext>&#160;alc&#160;</mtext><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>LiqNH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mtext>, alc&#160;</mtext><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Lindlar Catalyst</p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>aqKOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;Lindlar Catalyst","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, aq <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KOH</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>NaNH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>LiqNH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A trans alkene can be converted to a vicinal dihalide through a halogenation reaction. The vicinal dihalide can undergo double elimination to afford an alkyne. The alkyne can undergo partial reduction to give a cis alkene.</p><p>The reagents needed to convert&nbsp;trans<i><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>Ph</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math></i>&nbsp;to&nbsp;cis-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>Ph</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;are shown in the reaction scheme below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f915bf6b-e308-4d86-ad84-ed0ebbb3f799-9896079.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 431px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30422,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QSFk2GUrY99AMDep8n8SySL4Eu28OVqcq5nJvt5a5i0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />$\\Rightarrow$ Number of $\\mathrm{sp}^2 \\mathrm{C}$-atoms in product $\\mathrm{D}=7","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30619,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{HI}$ is a strong reducing agent.","$\\mathrm{H-I}$ bond is too strong to be broken homolytically.","$\\mathrm{I}$ atom combines with $\\mathrm{H}$ atom to give back $\\mathrm{HI}$.","Iodine atom is not reactive enough to add across a double bond."],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{HI}$ does not exhibit peroxide effect. $\\mathrm{HI}$ bond although dissociates easily into iodine radicals, they being bigger in size are not much reactive but recombine together to form iodine molecule.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30529,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Methylpropene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-Methylcyclopropane","But-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-ene","Cyclobutane"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eda51cbb-47fa-4b8a-a1a0-6a3fed47c059-image.png\" style=\"width: 368px; height: 125px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30395,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":3,"solution":"Statement I is false because Kolbe's electrolysis of sodium acetate produces ethane, not methane. The reaction is: $2\\text{CH}_3\\text{COONa} + 2\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\xrightarrow{\\text{Electrolysis}} \\text{CH}_3-\\text{CH}_3 + 2\\text{CO}_2 + \\text{H}_2 + 2\\text{NaOH}$. Decarboxylation of sodium ethanoate and the reaction of $\\text{CH}_3\\text{MgBr}$ with water do produce methane.<br><br>Statement II is true because the simplest unsaturated hydrocarbon is ethene ($\\text{C}_2\\text{H}_4$), which upon hydrogenation yields ethane, meaning methane cannot be prepared from unsaturated hydrocarbons. Additionally, the Wurtz reaction involves the coupling of two alkyl halide molecules to form an alkane with at least two carbon atoms ($2\\text{RX} + 2\\text{Na} \\rightarrow \\text{R}-\\text{R} + 2\\text{NaX}$), so methane cannot be prepared by this method.<br><br>Therefore, Statement I is false but Statement II is true.<br><br>Answer: Statement I is false but Statement II is true","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30528,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/46dfeb45-3aad-464d-9ce2-bad7ce042e28-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>ENT denote enantiomer of product.</p><p>The total number of products possible <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30488,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is the molar mass of the compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow></mfenced></math><br />mass of compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>molecular</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>mass of carbon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;....(i)</p><p>moles of carbon <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>molecular</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>carbon</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; ....(ii)</p><p>Thus, moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;from combustion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math>0.1 moles of carbon dioxide</p><p>Using POAC,<br />Thus, from (i) and (ii),<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mn>12</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>44</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30423,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/tz5Nc0BKJUZO_OoT-ZgZzUwNPP6u8LpMOR59IvASKHk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HsrvoxzdgrO-v22rL2PoyMEAhJ4kuCdTkm1ZmagdqXE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />St-I : Correct statement<br />St-II : In correct statement because product has chiral centre.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VmCW6VD9eCYZ5i-o1YTU32gofbBLs7CoGamLHL8ixM0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/36jJm1RnGZT-NNvqYkhmVvU66Mfd2iXktZG9YIaYeco.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yGiXCZsHAlcFldVav5sy6dARn1TmnM9nfiYFW4ZD1jc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WxHsauI_3MNcyYYi1lazndfA7BZ1uA_q5wlIjHM15p0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/E-vR9hlmuVkzvtszlt7wib-ekwZv27HRSGwSgO2UrLc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":30497,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; are both Markovnikov addition products.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; is Markovnikov product and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; is antiMarkovnikov product.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; are both anti-Markovnikov products.","&#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&#39; is Markovnikov and &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; is anti-<br />Markovnikov product."],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In the first step of hydroboration oxidation, the boron and hydrogen add to the same face of the double&nbsp;bond. In the second step, the OH takes the identical position occupied by the&nbsp;boron. Thus, the OH and H groups that are effectively added to the original&nbsp;double bond are cis. The overall addition takes place in anti Markovnikov&#39;s fashion.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de84a424-c210-4858-beed-5f72dbc0ff5c-image.png\" style=\"width: 337px; height: 104px;\" /></p><p>The reagent is mercury(II) acetate, which dissociates slightly to form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OAc</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OAc</mi><mo>)</mo></math> is the electrophile that adds to the pi bond. &bull; The intermediate is a three-membered ring called the mercurinium ion. Overall, the addition of water follows Markovnikov&rsquo;s rule</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5904aa24-215d-4fed-813f-437aea1279d6-e608ab7c-55ed-4f21-8315-c86bd214ce49-image.png\" style=\"width: 611px; height: 229px;\" /></p><p>The reaction does not suffer from rearrangements because there is no carbocation intermediate.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30520,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb5cfb34-449b-4ae8-822a-c7eb9d90836b-image.png\" style=\"width: 215px; height: 102px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81da926f-8bef-4106-870f-0405751867b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 287px; height: 145px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b6c1622a-585a-47df-b8f0-9a4a5e88551b-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 111px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/34c4e824-21b6-47eb-aa90-1d078dab2e23-image.png\" style=\"width: 302px; height: 106px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64921b98-b40c-46cc-a0b0-7d47bf17b484-9eca4ddc-c6f5-4a68-9940-559be6120830-image.png\" style=\"width: 689px; height: 147px;\" /></p><p>Major product will be formed by elimination reaction. Product having conjugated double bonds is more stable.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30476,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["B only","A only","C only","D only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The carbonyl compounds undergo Clemmenson&#39;s reduction in the presence of zinc amalgam and concentrated hydrochloric acid to form alkanes.&nbsp; The reagent in the Clemmenson&#39;s reduction effects the acid sensitive functional group. In the given reactant hydroxy group undergo dehydration to give alkene as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c87f71e0-afc7-42eb-8f2b-670c38c1d81f.png\" style=\"width: 509px; height: 88px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30413,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Benzene reacts with $\\text{CH}_3\\text{-CO-CH}_2\\text{-CH}_2\\text{-CO-Cl}$ in the presence of anhydrous $\\text{AlCl}_3$ (Friedel-Crafts acylation) to give product P (a keto-ketone).<br>P on treatment with aq. NaOH and heating undergoes intramolecular aldol condensation to give a cyclic enone Q.<br>Molecular mass of Q $= 157$<br>Percentage of oxygen in Q $= \\frac{16}{157} \\times 100 = 10.19\\% \\approx 10\\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30491,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>770</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>; (ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>; (iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>; (iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>; (ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cr</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>770</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>; (iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>; (iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>; (ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mo</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></math>; (iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>; (iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","(i)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mo</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></math>; (ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>; (iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>; (iv)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>It is a sequence of reactions where heptane is oxidised to methyl benzene, further oxidised to benzaldehyde,&nbsp;and finally cannizzaro reaction occurs to give the desired product.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de1383f0-284a-4555-ba72-f7681356e0de-6cde4d31-7c89-4ae9-ae60-a7247449c6f1-9894725_.PNG\" style=\"width: 512px; height: 357px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30454,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math>–Pentyne <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo></math> trans – <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> – butene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> – Pentane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo></math> trans – <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> – butene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math> – Pentyne <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo></math> Cis – <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> – butene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> – Pentane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo> </mo><mo>:</mo><mo> </mo><mi>Cis</mi><mo> </mo><mo>–</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math> – butene"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In palladium-catalyzed hydrogenations of alkynes, the Lindlar catalyst facilitates the addition of hydrogen to the alkyne to afford the corresponding alkene. When this catalyst is used, the addition of the hydrogen substituent always proceeds via syn addition (addition of the substituent on the same side of the bond).</p><p>But<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>yne when treated with sodium in liquid ammonia gives trans<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>butene. The reaction of alkyne with sodium in liquid ammonia produces sodamide in the process converting alkynes to alkenes. Mechanism of Birch Reduction: -Sodium in liquid ammonia produces solvated electrons.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/653c013f-d144-41e3-a3b4-073dcc847f30.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 372px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30482,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["B and C only","B, C and D only","A, C and D only","A and B only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>A: Cis - But-2-ene</p><p>B: Trans - But-2-ene</p><p>More polar molecules are more soluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>. Hence A &gt;B.</p><p>Molecules having higher dipole moments have higher boiling points due to larger intermolecular&nbsp;forces of attraction.&nbsp;More symmetric isomers have higher melting points due to better packing in crystalline lattice &amp; trans isomers are more symmetric than cis. Hence, in case of boiling point it is A&gt;B and in case of melting point it is B&gt;A.</p><p>cis-isomer has resultant of dipoles while in trans isomer dipole moments cancel out.&nbsp;</p><p>So, the correct answer is B, C and D only.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30509,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/898f93b8-c4be-48f1-a6c9-63e0ffe1934e-9706390_A.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 125px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5fe62876-ab9b-4e97-975e-4f1114541374-9706390_C.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 139px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d2f464ec-1c06-4635-82ef-898aad05f7a8-9-7-20221.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 139px;\" /></p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/83c8ed5d-1d3e-419d-943f-a5b4bcb110db-9706390_B.png\" style=\"width: 185px; height: 103px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3c65ae86-8aa4-49a2-810b-ee1d12a0e5cd-9706390_S.png\" style=\"width: 560px; height: 100px;\" /></p>It is&nbsp;oxymercuration&ndash;demercuration reaction. In this an alkene is treated with mercury(II) acetate,&nbsp;and the product is treated with sodium borohydride. The net result is a Markovnikov addition product without rearrangement.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30564,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8aa4b62b-5b63-4b8d-8484-1efddd35d05f-image.png\" style=\"width: 290px; height: 90px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12dba2de-6a72-4708-9050-a13caba38eff-image.png\" style=\"width: 297px; height: 93px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6e8df55e-e38f-4e6b-8db3-1fb12d575938-image.png\" style=\"width: 314px; height: 99px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/84a35af6-4f5c-41ab-a483-5866c9ad9a9e-image.png\" style=\"width: 329px; height: 98px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Benzene ring should not be attached to O atom otherwise it will yield phenol after reacting with<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HI</mi></math>&nbsp;so third option is prefect which gives benzyl iodide and it gives yellow precipitate of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgI</mi></math>&nbsp;after reacting with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>. Another product tautomerises and gives acetaldehyde which gives iodoform test.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/30e1567c-9bf4-4a1e-8ba8-b24cc19da75b-image.png\" style=\"width: 675px; height: 245px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30549,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>Sn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>KBr</mi></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>Fe</mi></mrow></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>Sn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>CuBr</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HBr</mi></mrow></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>HCl</mi></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>KBr</mi></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>Sn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mover><mo>/</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>NaBr</mi></mover></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The process of conversion of primary aromatic amines into its&nbsp;diazonium&nbsp;salt is called&nbsp;diazotization.&nbsp;</p><p>Diazonium&nbsp;salts are important synthetic intermediates that can undergo coupling&nbsp;reactions&nbsp;to form azo dyes and electrophilic substitution&nbsp;reactions&nbsp;to introduce functional groups.</p><p>The&nbsp;correct sequence of reagents used for converting nitrobenzene into m- dibromobenzene is found in option (b).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aefa6f34-12ff-4a77-af80-87730cc54f35-image.png\" style=\"width: 373px; height: 353px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30442,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["4-Ethyl-3,4-dimethyloctane","2,2,3,3-Tetramethylpentane","2,2,4,5-Tetramethylheptane","2,2,4,4-Tetramethylhexane"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PPA3I7bTwkUpvoM49AP9U1QgIhp30r-PiA9o-mE5NgA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30421,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["2","0","1","4"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yW3Ys9uSKQM9Bs55QFy8HgybxiI4Y9lwiAFNI2aIpiU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30416,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["5-methylhex-2-yne","Isopropylbut-1-yne","2-methylhex-3-yne","2-methylhex-2-yne"],"answer":2,"solution":"<br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30411,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<br>Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30511,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bb4d1de8-f02b-46dd-9386-9b2f1e9b741a-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 114px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66c70476-0946-465b-a165-913d749ec822-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f207be1-7e24-4472-951b-76df9122f4bd-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 129px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50ceb085-b841-4e1e-a4df-035e9484a82b-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 170px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0b324bec-2b88-472f-88dc-104adcd533e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 166px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30557,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28ed8306-c58b-4f58-8c94-60d705123b33-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 210px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47d4dbad-aa99-44f5-9ac5-5f4e776bb691-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/addd3787-737a-4f90-b37c-3d811fded215-image.png\" style=\"width: 176px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16a99e4b-8d32-44e8-a89e-062db3331d2b-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81002fbd-d7c8-46f2-8df6-971c9e8fc79b-image.png\" style=\"width: 406px; height: 400px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null}]